    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-11-23T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-11-23T08:00:00-05:00" n="88"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d88">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/3026</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-11-23T14:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 23, 1916, 2 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received November 24, 4.30 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4639. Press summary. The retirement of <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von
                        Jagow</persName> has evoked a great deal of criticism, for the most part
                    unkind, of his activities. The consensus of opinion is that although he was an
                    excellent Ambassador, he lacked most of the necessary qualifications of a
                    minister of foreign affairs. It is intimated that conflicts with other
                    departments <pb facs="0354" n="68" xml:id="pg_68"/> of the Government hastened
                    his resignation. The promotion of <persName corresp="#p_ZAFM1"
                        >Zimmermann</persName> is generally welcomed. <persName>Count
                        Reventlow</persName> expects a great deal of this forceful personality.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
